s of gender, class and race permeate this book, as the complex relationships between nurses, their medical colleagues, governments and the populations they nursed are examined in detail, using case studies which draw on exciting new sources. Many of the chapters are based on first-hand accounts of nurses and reveal that not all were motivated by patriotic vigour or altruism, but went out in search of adventure. The book will be an essential read for colonial historians, as well as historians of gender and ethnicity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNursingxHistory. 0aNursingxSocial aspects. 0aPublic health nursingzGreat BritainxColoniesxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aColonial.  aCulture.  aGender.  aNursing.  aPolitics.  aPost-colonial.  aRace.1 aApple, Rima D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong-Reid, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBest, Odette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryder, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCeleri Bellotti, Giancarlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnerton, Winifred C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, Angharad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Sue, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela